<br>
But now I'm just not enjoying the game at this point.  After experiencing the joy that is The Rathe (an encounter that was broken for as long as the players have been telling VI, me included) and beating it, and in the process, losing a half year lead on our server competition....to the Plane of Time, another zone that should have been functional and realistic within the expectations of the players that fought hard to get there, yet is not.  Plane of Time was not designed with forethought, and it showed with the G-Flux spell line.<br>
<br>
A few days after we got into Plane of Time, the G-Flux line of spells were disabled in TimeB, as was expected.  Now, VI is condeming the spell line since it is easier to nerf a very fun spell rather than fixing the appropriate zones with invisible walls, like they should have been designed with in the first place.<br>
<br>
I've always been appreciative to Verant for this game and their hard work on it, more so than most people.  But changing a spell line that is as much fun to use as G-Flux simply because it had non-conventional uses in Plane of Time goes too far in my book.  The correct fix was simple and to the point...disabling the spell in TimeB.  Changing the actual spell is wrong.<br>
<br>
I consider this change a kneejerk reaction, much like HoH summoning nerf.  Neither change adds to the fun factor of being a Wiz, or any other class for that matter...it just highlights to me the current concept in how to fix things:  Use a huge heavy blunt object to fix a china cup.<br>
<br>
Disable the spell line in the zones that you do not want it used in...that is a fix we can all appreciate.  Please leave the spell alone.<br>
<br>
Abadacus RuneMaster<br>
Gnomish Arcanist<br>
Afterlife <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bayler>Bayler</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/15/03 11:01 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: emm</span><hr size=1> I (as a rogue) repeatedly pulled the human skeleton to the zoneline in my 40's by sneaking in the front door.  Now, I confess that that's probably not what the quest designer had in mind either; but nonetheless, the quest *is* doable by a group of low 40's without Gravflux, without the flagpole, and without the taunt trick.<br>
<br>
But for sake or argument, let's say that pulling to the bottom floor isn't allowed.  I agree that a single group of low 40's won't be able to fight their way up to the ramparts.  But keep in mind that CoM is a *raid zone*.  You've got tons of reaver hunts for druids and rangers.  And up at the top, you've got epic mobs for enchanters, mages, and shamen.  The human skeleton, in fact, is just down the hall from a room that pretty much any 2nd floor CoM raid *is* going to stop in.  (You don't actually have to go into the room, but it's a good place for a med break, and if you don't clear it out you'll risk adds going up the ramp.)<br>
<br>
Personally, I believe the notion that the quest wasn't intended for level 39's.  Maybe they just made it level 39 so that if you were driven enough or lucky enough to be able to get it that early, you'd be able to scribe it right away.  But I'm not a subscriber to the idea that you're entitled to every spell the moment you ding. <p>Bayler - Marauder/Deceiver - Xev<br>
